# arvo-bits-contracts. Design

The bit-level trait declarations. Every trait here is `pub const trait`.
Default-method bodies reference `Bits<N, S, Sign>` and the bare
primitive containers; consumer call sites pull this crate to bind to
the trait surface, then reach the concrete impls in `arvo-bits` via
blanket dispatch. `#![no_std]`, no alloc.

The Sign axis on `Bits<N, S, Sign>` (round 202604280500) is invisible
at the trait surface; bit-level operations act on raw bit patterns
which are sign-agnostic by construction. Default `Sign = Unsigned` at
the Bits surface keeps existing call sites unchanged.

Depends on `notko`, `arvo-transparent`, `arvo-strategy`, `arvo-storage`.

## HasBitWidth

```rust
pub const trait HasBitWidth {
    const WIDTH: USize;
}
```

How many logical bits a type occupies. Renamed from `BitWidth` per
round 202604271346 to free that name for the `Width` newtype in
`arvo-storage`. Const trait so `T::WIDTH` works in const fn bodies
under generic-T.

## BitAccess

```rust
pub const trait BitAccess: HasBitWidth + Copy {
    fn bit(self, idx: USize) -> Bool;
    fn with_bit_set(self, idx: USize) -> Self;
    fn with_bit_cleared(self, idx: USize) -> Self;
    fn with_bit_toggled(self, idx: USize) -> Self;
}
```

Individual bit manipulation. Functional style, no mutation. `idx` is
from LSB.

## BitSequence

```rust
pub const trait BitSequence: HasBitWidth + Copy {
    fn trailing_zeros(self) -> USize;
    fn leading_zeros(self) -> USize;
    fn count_ones(self) -> USize;
    fn count_zeros(self) -> USize;
    fn is_zero(self) -> Bool;
}
```

Scanning and counting. Maps to hardware intrinsics (`cttz`, `ctlz`,
`popcnt`). The primitives that mask iteration uses internally.

## BitLogic

```rust
pub const trait BitLogic: HasBitWidth + Copy {
    fn bitor(self, other: Self) -> Self;
    fn bitand(self, other: Self) -> Self;
    fn bitnot(self) -> Self;
    fn bitxor(self, other: Self) -> Self;
    fn shl(self, n: USize) -> Self;
    fn shr(self, n: USize) -> Self;
    fn clear_lowest_set_bit(self) -> Self
    where
        Self: BitAccess + BitSequence;
}
```

Whole-word bitwise logic. Single-instruction on the backing
primitive. Hot-only surface (other strategies' wider containers make
whole-word ops meaningless at the logical-width level).

`clear_lowest_set_bit` has a default body via `BitSequence` +
`BitAccess`; concrete types override with the BLSR-equivalent fast
path.

## BitPrim family

```rust
pub const trait BitPrim: Copy + ConstParamTy_ + ... {
    // primitive-bridge methods on bare u8/u16/u32/u64
}

pub const trait UBitContainer<const N: u8> {
    type Container: BitPrim;
}

pub const trait IBitContainer<const N: u8> {
    type Container: BitPrim;
}
```

The primitive-bridge family. `BitPrim` is the sealed surface that
`u8`, `u16`, `u32`, `u64`, `u128` (and signed counterparts through
`i128`) implement, plus `MultiContainer<HiT, LoT>` for the multi-value
storage shape at logical widths beyond a single native primitive
(round 202604280500). Used by blanket impls in `arvo-bits` to delegate
from `Bits<N, S, Sign>::to_raw()` to the primitive's bit method, then
`Bits::from_raw(...)` wraps the result. Const trait throughout.

## Narrow

```rust
pub const trait Narrow<T> {
    fn narrow_to<const N: u16>(self) -> T
    where
        Self: Sized;

    fn narrow_to_unmasked<const N: u16>(self) -> T
    where
        Self: Sized;
}

pub type Narrowed<const N: u16, T> = T;
```

The unified mask-and-cast bridge for cross-primitive narrowing.
`narrow_to::<N>` composes `Mask<W>::mask_for_width(N)` (from
`arvo-mask-contracts`) with `BitLogic::and` then the `as` operator
to cast to the target primitive type, sound under the mask
precondition.

`narrow_to_unmasked::<N>` skips the mask op for the hot case where
the high bits are already zero (chained narrow, bitfield extraction
that just-shifted-down, value carried through a Bits<M, ...>
projection of equal-or-narrower width). The precondition is the
consumer's responsibility; calling with non-zero high bits produces
silent garbage in the unmasked path.

Moved here from the previously-separate `arvo-narrow-contracts`
crate during round 202604280034. The merge is justified because
every consumer of `Narrow` already depends on `BitLogic` for the
default-body composition; the single-trait crate split was ceremony
without transitive-footprint benefit. Concrete impls live in
`arvo-narrow` (cross-primitive) and may extend into `arvo-bitmask`
(mask-using).

`Narrowed<const N: u16, T>` is a cosmetic alias for the result of
`narrow_to::<N>` so consumer signatures read `fn foo() -> Narrowed<13, u16>`
instead of bare `u16`. The const-generic `N` is documentation only at
the type level (the value has been narrowed to `N` bits but the
carrier is still `T`).

The const-generic param widened from `u8` to `u16` in Pass F of round
202604281000, matching the `Bits<const N: u16>` widening at the same
pass. The widening accommodates reachable widths up to 65535; concrete
narrow impls cover 1..=256.

